When drawing backgrounds make sure the lines are thinner than the lines used in the foreground, if the lines are the same thickness you run the risk of confusing the distance between shapes in the drawing. 
.
Remember the farther things are the more out of focus they are and thinner lines tend to give that illusion.
.
Drawing is a series of comparisons so you're always drawing stuff compared to the other shapes, figures, and objects, so make sure if you want to make things seem natural to always have everything following the same rules and be different in relation to eachother.
Hope that made sense

Apparently any art content over 10 seconds instagram doesn't push out, I should probably add the subway surfer clips too, but srsly tho this app's algorithm is very flipfloppy and people take it too seriously for an app people check while they take a dump

And it's all because people who rely on tricks and gimmicks post way more often and more effectively than you
So the app forms around their patterns

I see a lotta tricks being used as a person who understands this social media stuff now a bit better, but all the tricks mean nothing if you don't like what you do, if your an art creator just make art, and post it multiple times and post everyday, and you'll grow slowly without burning out, just ask yourself would anyone watch this video, then regardless of the answer post it anyway, if you draw just put it out there.
Don't do it for going viral but that would be nice too, and technically if you post more even if it sucks you will increase your chances of posting better stuff which will lead to eventually to a bigger presence,
Like they say the best time to plant an avocado was 10 years ago, it's a long game, just do it without expecting nothing 
I mean there's people who pretend they know stuff and share it online and get millions of clicks, if you got some knowledge or do some cool stuff share it,
There's too many scammers and uncreative people spamming the internet,
While people who make cool stuff always second guessing themselves and waiting for tomorrow and being lazy,
I know many good artists, craftspeople, and knowledgeable people that don't want to do social media stuff cuz they think people won't pay attention to what they do or won't appreciate it, 
That doesn't matter tho just share what you know you never know who you'll help or inspire
Just like mr. Nike said, just do it

Anyway, enjoy the art, an old sketch from a while back

.
.

Make sure to plan the basics thoroughly, get everything planned, do not all in one thing of the drawing because if you didn't plan the rest it probably sucks, here I fully drew the face and I really like it, so when I realized it's out of place compares to the other figure I was really disappointed, 
Sometimes you don't want to erase what you spent time and energy on, that's why you gotta draw loose, fast, and keep the early phase of drawing simple.
I had to go get my light board to trace the face I drew onto another paper, ended up breaking the lighboard by accident ,
Sometimes you cause yourself pain by being impatient 😅, 
So now I can finish this when my new light box arrives, but I'll probably be busy again, and I'm to lazy to draw most of what I drew in the final drawing 

.

When I was still doing pages for practice I felt the hardest thing to do was make sure the viewers eye flowed through the panels and page in the order I wanted them to.

The best thing that helped me out was thinking of the page like a funnel, bring the readers eyes down through the page and make sure the main subject in each panel points to the next panel somehow. 

To point to the next panel, you can use perspective, a gesture or pose, a character's eyes, objects, or even a character pointing. making sure the art doesn't get a reader to stop is important in drawing comics, so always trying to be creative with how you lay out the panel, and having them be energetic will always be an important focus.

In these two panels you see the character in the first panel slightly looks to the next one, and in the second one the perspective and the car point to the bottom left, so naturally the reader will then follow those directions.

Hope this helps ✌😁

For years I've always tried to draw batman my own way, I always felt like many artists, no matter how well they draw him, they leave out  the menacing side to his costume, it's something I try to capture, but I still feel like I'm not there, my favorite batman costumes are the ones drawn by Jason fabok, neal adams, Kelley jones, and tim sale. They're the ones that always give the most batman feel, don't really know how to describe it, but it's also definitely the way they render shadows. Some of the best art advice I've ever gotten in terms of rendering was from one of the coolest people I've met, the legendary Tim Sale, he said to always aim for higher contrast rather than go for too much lines, rendering with lines takes away too much from the shape, big blocky shadows or small ones will always define the shapes better, especially in comic art, he explained it way better than I can explain it here 😅. It's still hard to render that way but the more I aim towards it I feel the clearer my art becomes.

.
.

After years of drawing, these are my preferred tools. I get dm'd the question a lot about what tools are best, honestly it doesn't matter as long as you draw with them, because if you can't draw you won't appreciate how the tool helps you.
 You really just need a pencil and a pen that can draw in every line width, then two brushes a small one and a big one and some ink you like, and the erasers are self explanatory, the kneaded eraser makes your life easier when it comes to sketching lightly. These tools combined with a half liter of ink probably cost me less than 40 dollars, and I've been using the ink and these supplies for a few years now, when it comes to drawing in ink, you shouldn't be aiming for the fancy or expensive, I see too many people spending too much money to just be frustrated by their supplies. Keep it simple that way you can know your limit then you can figure out if you need more tools. But when it comes to painting I think that's when supplies can become a nightmare, I'll do another post on that. Oh, and posca white acrylic markers are a great whiteout.
#art #drawing #arttools #drawingtips
